docs.abstract: The proliferation of cyberattacks by rivals is presenting a challenge to the Biden administration as it seeks to deter intrusions on government and corporate systems.
docs.snippet: The proliferation of cyberattacks by rivals is presenting a challenge to the Biden administration as it seeks to deter intrusions on government and corporate systems.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Just as it plans to begin retaliating against Russia for the large-scale hacking of American government agencies and corporations discovered late last year, the Biden administration faces a new cyberattack that raises the question of whether it will have to strike back at another major adversary: China.

headline.main: Preparing for Retaliation Against Russia, U.S. Confronts Hacking by China
headline.print_headline: Biden Is Tested in How to React to Cyberattacks From Russia and China

docs.abstract: When Google forced out two well-known artificial intelligence experts, a long-simmering research controversy burst into the open.

docs.lead_paragraph: Hundreds of people gathered for the first lecture at what had become the world’s most important conference on artificial intelligence — row after row of faces. Some were East Asian, a few were Indian, and a few were women. But the vast majority were white men. More than 5,500 people attended the meeting, five years ago in Barcelona, Spain.

headline.main: Who Is Making Sure the A.I. Machines Aren’t Racist?

docs.lead_paragraph: When coronavirus vaccines first became available, state health officials in Virginia turned to software recommended by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention to schedule appointments. docs.abstract: The intelligence agencies missed massive intrusions by Russia and China, forcing the administration and Congress to look for solutions, including closer partnership with private industry.
docs.snippet: The intelligence agencies missed massive intrusions by Russia and China, forcing the administration and Congress to look for solutions, including closer partnership with private industry.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The sophisticated hacks pulled off by Russia and China against a broad array of government and industrial targets in the United States — and the failure of the intelligence agencies to detect them — are driving the Biden administration and Congress to rethink how the nation should protect itself from growing cyberthreats.

headline.main: White House Weighs New Cybersecurity Approach After Failure to Detect Hacks
